@database "MUIResi"
@NODE Main "MUIResi"
Simple  program  that allows you to enter a resistor color code by clicking
on a colored gadget array. You may choose resistors from 3 to 6 bands.

Requires:

 - WB 2.0, better 2.1, even better 3.0
 - MUI V8

Features:

 - MUI Application, can be controlled via mouse or keyboard
 - fully localized (>= WB 2.1) (German catalog included)
 - Allocates pens (>= WB 3.0)

This  application works best on a high resolution 32 color WB. If you don't
have  such a WB then go into MUIPrefs/system page and set the public screen
to  a  highres screen with enough colors. If you don't have high resolution
screens you will have to select a tiny font.
		@{" MUIResi Main Window " link WI_main }
@ENDNODE
@NODE WI_main "MUIResi"
The main window consists of three parts.

The  topmost  object  is  an image of the selected resistor, with its value
below.

In  the  middle  part  is the array of gadgets with which you can enter the
color code.  The left column is associated to the leftmost band, and so on.
Just klick on some colors to see what's going on.

At  the  bottom  is  the  cycle  gadget  to  select the number of bands the
resistor has.
		@{" Resistor Image " link GR_resi_image }
		@{" Resistor Value " link TX_resi_value }
		@{" Gadget Array " link GR_gadget_array }
		@{" Number of Bands " link GR_bands }
@ENDNODE
@NODE GR_resi_image "Resistor Image"
This is an image of what the chosen resistor would look like. If there were
enough  free  pens  availabe, you should see 3 to 6 colored bands. If there
were  insufficient  free  pens,  you will see false colors or just a boring
pattern.

No input is possible here.
@NODE TX_resi_value "Resistor Value"
This  is  the  value (resistance) of the resistor shown above. If availabe,
also  the  tolerance  and the temerature coefficient is shown. For example,
the  string  "2.2  kOhm,  5 %" means, that the resistor has a resistance of
2200 Ohms plus or minus 5 percent.

@ENDNODE
@NODE GR_gadget_array "Gadget Array"
This  is  the array of gadgets with which you can enter the color code. The
left  column  is  associated to the leftmost band, and so on. Just klick on
some colors to see what's going on.
@ENDNODE
@NODE GR_bands "Number of Bands"
With  this  Gadget you may choose resistors from 3 to 6 bands.  Most carbon
layerd resistors have 4 rings, the metal film resistors usually have 5 or 6
bands.

If  you  choose  3 or 4 bands the displayed resistor will get a light brown
background,  with  5  or 6 bands it will become light green.  This imitates
the coloring of many standard resistors but has no other effect.
@ENDNODE
